The head of the world's largest dry-goods business, John G. Shedd, presi-



dentpresident of Marshall Field & Company of Chicago, attaches importance to environment. That is, while a man may possess "success qualities," he is not likely to attain the highest success unless he goes where opportunities for such success are most plentiful. Mr. Shedd was born and brought up on a farm in New Hampshire;









but, not liking farm labor, he got a job in a village store.
